.START 

The World Bank and its affiliate, the International Development Association, approved $275.3 million in loans to India, Kenya and Somalia. 

India will get $145 million from the World Bank and $55 million from the IDA to help finance technological research centers and imports of capital goods and foreign technology for use by about 1,200 industrial companies. 

Kenya will receive $46.8 million from the IDA to expand coffee production and processing facilities, and Somalia will receive $28.5 million from the IDA for agricultural irrigation projects. 

The World Bank loan to India will be at a variable interest rate, currently 7.74% a year.
The IDA credits will be interest-free except for administrative fees. 

